  • Horsepower is right skewed, There are roughly two peaks one of the peaks constitute the most of the frequent Horsepower as 150.
  • Weight is right skewed.
  • Acceleration is almost symetrically distributed.

Scaling

In [46]:
cols = ['Miles_per_gallon','displacement','horsepower','weight','acceleration']
cardata=df[['Miles_per_gallon','Cylinder','displacement','horsepower','weight','acceleration','launchedyear','origin']]
carscaled=cardata.apply(zscore)
pp = sns.pairplot(carscaled[cols], height=1.8, aspect=1.8,
                  plot_kws=dict(edgecolor="k", linewidth=0.5),
                  diag_kind="kde", diag_kws=dict(shade=True));

fig = pp.fig 
fig.subplots_adjust(top=0.93, wspace=0.3);
t = fig.suptitle('Pairwise Plots', fontsize=14);

We can derive following conclusions :

  • We can take an estimate of what is the minimum number of clusters we get in the dataframe. For example.
  • Displacement could contrirbute to minimum 3 groups to the final cluster.
  • We can also notice a strong positive co-relation between weight and displacement and weight and horsepower.
  • We can also notice that Miles per gallon is having negative correlation, with respect to displacement, horsepower and weight and it seems to only impact acceleration value.
  • Increase in number of cylinders contribute to the increase in displacement,horsepower and weight and it also seems to bring down the average/Miles_per_gallon
  • We can draw a heatmap and get an accurate value for the correlation among the variables.

Analysis through K-Means

In [20]:
#Finding optimal number of clusters
from scipy.spatial.distance import cdist #Calculating pairwaise distance between each pair of input points.
clusters=[2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8]
distortions=[]
silhouettes=[]
for k in clusters:
  model=KMeans(n_clusters=k)
  model.fit(carscaled)
  prediction=model.predict(carscaled)
  dist=cdist(carscaled,model.cluster_centers_,'euclidean') #Calculates the distance between centroid to each of the points.
  mindist=np.min(dist,axis=1) #Minimum distance between centroid to each point.
  distortions.append(sum(mindist)/carscaled.shape[0]) #Calculating Mean distortion

#Plotting for Mean cluster distance per cluster combination.

plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
plt.subplot(1,2,1)
plt.plot(clusters,distortions,'bx-')
plt.xlabel('Number of clusters')
plt.ylabel('Average Distance')
plt.title('Selecting k with elbow method');

plt.subplot(1,2,2)
clusters=[2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8]
for k in clusters:
  model=KMeans(n_clusters=k)
  model.fit(carscaled)
  cluster_labels = model.labels_
  silhouettes.append(silhouette_score(carscaled,cluster_labels))

plt.plot(clusters,silhouettes,'bx-')
plt.xlabel('Number of clusters')
plt.ylabel('silhouette score')
plt.title('Selecting k with silhouette SCORE');
  • From Elbow Method, we can say that the elbow is around 3,5.
  • As Evident from the Pairplot we could easily picture that minimum groups that could be formed is around 3.
  • For proper score calculation, we could pick up the silhoutte scores from corresponding clusters.

Analysis through Dendogram,Cophenetic index,Linkages

In [35]:
z=linkage(carscaled,metric='euclidean',method='average')
c,dist=cophenet(z,pdist(carscaled))
print(c)
plt.figure(figsize=(35, 10))
plt.title('Agglomerative Hierarchical Clustering Dendogram')
plt.xlabel('sample index')
plt.ylabel('Distance')
dendrogram(z, leaf_rotation=90.,color_threshold = 40, leaf_font_size=8. )
plt.tight_layout()

Optimum number of clusters:

  • As we can see in both the cases, when we cut around 3 we see a clear 4 clusters in case of average method linkage.
  • When we consider around 3 in case of complete linkage we can see very many clusters and the distance between each cluster is quite close so we can finally decide to cut around 6, we are getting 4 clusters. *Therefore we can reach our conclusion of getting 4 clusters from the Hierarchial clustering mechanism.

Model generation

In [44]:
# importing library
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression

# Normalise the dimensions for both the scenarios
x1=carscaled.copy()
yK=df_for_K_means['Cluster']
yH=df_for_Hierarchicy['Labels']

modelK=LinearRegression() #for K_means
modelH=LinearRegression() #for hierarachy

modelK.fit(x1,yK);
modelH.fit(x1,yH);

print("Score for K_Means Dataframe",modelK.score(x1,yK))
print("Score for Hierarchial Dataframe",modelH.score(x1,yH))

print("Coefficents for K_Means Dataframe :",modelK.coef_)
print("Coefficents for Hierarchial Dataframe: ",modelH.coef_)

Score for K_Means Dataframe 0.8877900831204767
Score for Hierarchial Dataframe 0.9604172145404499
Coefficents for K_Means Dataframe : [ 0.14205523 -0.24653749 -0.12421309 -0.15015992 -0.01108034 -0.02193816
 -0.02953897  0.20867407]
Coefficents for Hierarchial Dataframe:  [-0.05783335  0.70469773  0.03385812  0.01146368  0.02453932 -0.03159249
 -0.0210882   0.02335419]

We can derive following conclusion:

  • K_Means gives best result when compared for cluster k=3 as compared to cluster k=5
  • Hierarchial clustering mechanism gives a 96% R^2 score where it outperforms K_means model.
  • This difference in the score is largely due to the fact that the Hierarchial clustering clusters the data based on the distance between their indivisual datapoints whereas K_means iteratively takes up the centriod approach, which seems to be unable to properly cluster the datapoints in a clear manner of k=3 cluster.

Improvements

  1. The dataset should have some more columns aswell like price so that there could be a better classification based on amount.
  2. The dataset should consist of few more rows so that the insample data should learn more.
